#, no-wrap
msgid "term:dwc[dwc:georeferenceProtocol]"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 0500-sharing-data.en.adoc:56
msgid "a citation of a published set of rules used to determine a <<georeference>>. For example, “Georeferencing Quick Reference Guide 2020”. Any deviations from the cited protocol should be noted in term:dwc[dwc:georeferenceRemarks]"
msgstr ""

#. type: Labeled list
#: 0500-sharing-data.en.adoc:57
#, no-wrap
msgid "term:dwc[dwc:georeferenceSources]"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 0500-sharing-data.en.adoc:58
msgid "a list of maps, <<gazetteer,gazetteers>>, or other resources used to <<georeference>> the <<locality>>. Should be specific enough that someone else can locate and use the same sources. Example: \"USGS 1:24000 Florence Montana Quad 1967; Terrametrics 2008, Google Earth\"."
msgstr ""

#. type: Labeled list
#: 0500-sharing-data.en.adoc:59
#, no-wrap
msgid "term:dwc[dwc:georeferenceVerificationStatus]"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 0500-sharing-data.en.adoc:60
msgid "an indicator of the extent to which the <<georeference>> has been verified to represent the best possible spatial description for the occurrence record. By default a newly created georeference should have the status \"requires verification\". Beyond that, there are really only two other functionally distinct possibilities, either \"verified\" (by the person mentioned in term:dwc[dwc:georeferencedBy]), and \"verified by collector\" or equivalent, to designate that the georeference was reviewed for that specific record by the person who recorded it to begin with, and that it can not be further improved. This is the ideal status to aspire to."
msgstr ""

#. type: Labeled list
#: 0500-sharing-data.en.adoc:61
#, no-wrap
msgid "term:dwc[dwc:georeferenceRemarks]"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 0500-sharing-data.en.adoc:62
msgid "any notes or comments about the spatial description, deviations from the cited protocol, assumptions, or problems with <<georeference,georeferencing>>. For example, \"locality too vague to georeference\"."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ===
#: 0500-sharing-data.en.adoc:63
#, no-wrap
msgid "Generalizing Georeferences for Sensitive Taxa and Locations"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 0500-sharing-data.en.adoc:66
msgid "As recommended elsewhere in this document, <<georeference,georeferences>> should be recorded and stored at the best possible resolution and <<precision>>. If, however, the <<location>> of a taxon is regarded as sensitive for some reason following the guidelines as set out in https://doi.org/10.15468/doc-5jp4-5g10[Chapman 2020^] and https://doi.org/10.15468/doc-b02j-gt10[Chapman & Grafton 2008^], and it is agreed that the detailed location information should not be shared, we recommend, that the data only be <<generalization,generalized>> at the time of sharing or publishing of the data."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 0500-sharing-data.en.adoc:68
msgid "We recommend that if data are to be generalized that it be done by reducing the number of decimal places (for example when using <<decimal degrees>>) at which the data are published (https://doi.org/10.15468/doc-b02j-gt10[Chapman & Grafton 2008^], https://doi.org/10.15468/doc-5jp4-5g10[Chapman 2020^]). Good practice dictates that whatever you do to generalize the data, it be documented so that users of the data know what reliance can be placed on them. As far as the generalization of georeferencing data is concerned it is important to record that the data have been generalized using a ‘_decimal geographic grid_’, and record both:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 0500-sharing-data.en.adoc:70
msgid "Precision of the data provided (e.g. 0.1 degree; 0.001 degree, etc.)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 0500-sharing-data.en.adoc:71
msgid "Precision of the data stored or held (e.g. 0.0001 degree, 0.1 minute, 1 second, etc.)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 0500-sharing-data.en.adoc:73
msgid "We recommend that when recording the degree of generalization of data, that <<spatial fit,Spatial Fit>> (<<Determining Spatial Fit>>) be used. For example, the degree to which a record has been generalized to obfuscate the georeference will be a number greater than 1 (see <<img-spatial-fit>> and https://doi.org/10.15468/doc-5jp4-5g10[Chapman 2020^])."
